# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: simula-language
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:simula-language/coroutine] They have been described as "functions whose execution you can pause".
[src:simula-language/coroutine] Melvin Conway coined the term *coroutine* in 1958 when he applied it to the construction of an assembly program.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] The first published explanation of the coroutine appeared later, in 1963.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] There is no single precise definition of coroutine.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] 2. the execution of a coroutine is suspended as control leaves it, only to carry on where it left off when control re-enters the coroutine at some later stage.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] 3. whether a coroutine is able to suspend its execution from within nested function calls.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] Such a coroutine is a *stackful coroutine*.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] One to the contrary is called *stackless coroutines*, where unless marked as coroutine, a regular function can't use the keyword `yield`.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] The paper "Revisiting Coroutines" published in 2009 proposed the term *full coroutine* to denote one that supports first-class coroutine and is stackful.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] Full Coroutines deserve their own name in that they have the same expressive power as one-shot continuations and delimited continuations.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] Full coroutines are either symmetric or asymmetric.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] Importantly, whether a coroutine is symmetric or asymmetric has no bearing on how expressive it can be, though full coroutines are more expressive than non-full coroutines.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] While their expressive power is the same, asymmetrical coroutines more closely resemble routine based control structures in the sense that control is always passed back to the invoker, which programmers may find more familiar.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] Subroutines are special cases of coroutines.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] When subroutines are invoked, execution begins at the start, and once a subroutine exits, it is finished; an instance of a subroutine only returns once, and does not hold state between invocations.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] By contrast, coroutines can exit by calling other coroutines, which may later return to the point where they were invoked in the original coroutine; from the coroutine's point of view, it is not exiting but calling another coroutine.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] Thus, a coroutine instance holds state, and varies between invocations; there can be multiple instances of a given coroutine at once.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] The difference between calling another coroutine by means of "yielding" to it and simply calling another routine (which then, also, would return to the original point), is that the relationship between two coroutines which yield to each other is not that of caller-callee, but instead symmetric.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] Any subroutine can be translated to a coroutine which does not call *yield*.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] Here is a simple example of how coroutines can be useful.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] Suppose you have a consumer-producer relationship where one routine creates items and adds them to a queue and another removes items from the queue and uses them.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] For reasons of efficiency, you want to add and remove several items at once.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] The queue is then completely filled or emptied before yielding control to the other coroutine using the *yield* command.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] The further coroutines calls are starting right after the *yield*, in the outer coroutine loop.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] Although this example is often used as an introduction to multithreading, two threads are not needed for this: the *yield* statement can be implemented by a jump directly from one routine into the other.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] However, coroutines are cooperatively multitasked, whereas threads are typically preemptively multitasked.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] Coroutines provide concurrency, because they allow tasks to be performed out of order or in a changeable order, without changing the overall outcome, but they do not provide parallelism, because they do not execute multiple tasks simultaneously.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] It is possible to implement coroutines using preemptively-scheduled threads, in a way that will be transparent to the calling code, but some of the advantages (particularly the suitability for hard-realtime operation and relative cheapness of switching between them) will be lost.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] Generators, also known as semicoroutines, are a subset of coroutines.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] That is, since generators are primarily used to simplify the writing of iterators, the `yield` statement in a generator does not specify a coroutine to jump to, but rather passes a value back to a parent routine.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] A number of implementations of coroutines for languages with generator support but no native coroutines (e.g.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] Python before 2.5) use this or a similar model.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] Using coroutines for state machines or concurrency is similar to using mutual recursion with tail calls, as in both cases the control changes to a different one of a set of routines.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] However, coroutines are more flexible and generally more efficient.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] Further, each mutually recursive call of a subroutine requires a new stack frame (unless tail call elimination is implemented), while passing control between coroutines uses the existing contexts and can be implemented simply by a jump.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] Coroutines originated as an assembly language method, but are supported in some high-level programming languages.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] Java does not have native or library support for coroutines, but it can call Kotlin coroutines `kotlinx.coroutines` (though this is not ideal and would require a Java wrapper over Kotlin).
[src:simula-language/coroutine] Since continuations can be used to implement coroutines, programming languages that support them can also quite easily support coroutines.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] As of 2003, many of the most popular programming languages, including C and its derivatives, do not have built-in support for coroutines within the language or their standard libraries.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] This is, in large part, due to the limitations of stack-based subroutine implementation.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] An exception is the C++ library Boost.Context, part of Boost, which supports context swapping on ARM, MIPS, PowerPC, SPARC and x86 on POSIX, Mac OS X and Windows.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] Coroutines can be built upon Boost.Context.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] Conditionals within the code result in the execution of different code paths on successive calls, based on the values of the state variables.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] Another typical response is to implement an explicit state machine in the form of a large and complex switch statement or via a goto statement, particularly a computed goto.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] Such implementations are considered difficult to understand and maintain, and a motivation for coroutine support.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] Threads, and to a lesser extent fibers, are an alternative to coroutines in mainstream programming environments today.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] Threads provide facilities for managing the real-time cooperative interaction of *simultaneously* executing pieces of code.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] Threads are widely available in environments that support C (and are supported natively in many other modern languages), are familiar to many programmers, and are usually well-implemented, well-documented and well-supported.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] However, as they solve a large and difficult problem they include many powerful and complex facilities and have a correspondingly difficult learning curve.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] As such, when a coroutine is all that is needed, using a thread can be overkill.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] One important difference between threads and coroutines is that threads are typically preemptively scheduled while coroutines are not.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] Because threads can be rescheduled at any instant and can execute concurrently, programs using threads must be careful about locking.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] In contrast, because coroutines can only be rescheduled at specific points in the program and do not execute concurrently, programs using coroutines can often avoid locking entirely.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] This property is also cited as a benefit of event-driven or asynchronous programming.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] Since fibers are cooperatively scheduled, they provide an ideal base for implementing coroutines above.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] However, system support for fibers is often lacking compared to that for threads.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] In order to implement general-purpose coroutines, a second call stack must be obtained, which is a feature not directly supported by the C language.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] A reliable (albeit platform-specific) way to achieve this is to use a small amount of inline assembly to explicitly manipulate the stack pointer during initial creation of the coroutine.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] This is the approach recommended by Tom Duff in a discussion on its relative merits vs. the method used by Protothreads.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] On platforms which provide the POSIX sigaltstack system call, a second call stack can be obtained by calling a springboard function from within a signal handler to achieve the same goal in portable C, at the cost of some extra complexity.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] C libraries complying to POSIX or the Single Unix Specification (SUSv3) provided such routines as getcontext, setcontext, makecontext and swapcontext, but these functions were declared obsolete in POSIX 1.2008.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] Once a second call stack has been obtained with one of the methods listed above, the setjmp and longjmp functions in the standard C library can then be used to implement the switches between coroutines.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] These functions save and restore, respectively, the stack pointer, program counter, callee-saved registers, and any other internal state as required by the ABI, such that returning to a coroutine after having yielded restores all the state that would be restored upon returning from a function call.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] Minimalist implementations, which do not piggyback off the setjmp and longjmp functions, may achieve the same result via a small block of inline assembly which swaps merely the stack pointer and program counter, and clobbers all other registers.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] This can be significantly faster, as setjmp and longjmp must conservatively store all registers which may be in use according to the ABI, whereas the clobber method allows the compiler to store (by spilling to the stack) only what it knows is actually in use.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] Due to the lack of direct language support, many authors have written their own libraries for coroutines which hide the above details.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] Russ Cox's libtask library is a good example of this genre.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] It uses the context functions if they are provided by the native C library; otherwise it provides its own implementations for ARM, PowerPC, Sparc, and x86.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] Other notable implementations include libpcl, coro, lthread, libCoroutine, libconcurrency, libcoro, ribs2, libdill., libaco, and libco.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] In addition to the general approach above, several attempts have been made to approximate coroutines in C with combinations of subroutines and macros.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] Simon Tatham's contribution, based on Duff's device, is a notable example of the genre, and is the basis for Protothreads and similar implementations.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] C++20 introduced standardized coroutines as stackless functions that can be suspended in the middle of execution and resumed at a later point.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] The suspended state of a coroutine is stored on the heap.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] Implementation of this standard is ongoing, with the G++ and MSVC compilers currently fully supporting standard coroutines in recent versions.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] A generator class for synchronous and lazy-evaluated ranges, `std::generator`, was added in C++23.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] A proper task class, `std::execution::task`, was introduced in C++26.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] It is invoked using `std::execution::sync_wait()`, which returns `std::optional<std::tuple<Ts...>>`.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] This is an example of C++20 coroutines with the C++26 `std::execution::task` class.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] C# 2.0 added semi-coroutine (generator) functionality through the iterator pattern and `yield` keyword.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] Cloroutine is a third-party library providing support for stackless coroutines in Clojure.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] It's implemented as a macro, statically splitting an arbitrary code block on arbitrary var calls and emitting the coroutine as a stateful function.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] D implements coroutines as its standard library class `core.thread.Fiber` for a fiber.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] A generator (`std.concurrency.Generator`) makes it trivial to expose a fiber function as an input range (`std.range.interfaces.InputRange`), making any fiber compatible with existing range algorithms.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] Go has a built-in concept of "goroutines", a type of green thread which are lightweight, independent processes managed by the Go runtime.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] A new goroutine can be started using the "go" keyword.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] Each goroutine has a variable-size stack which can be expanded as needed.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] Goroutines generally communicate using Go's built-in channels.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] However, goroutines are not coroutines (for instance, local data does not persist between successive calls).
[src:simula-language/coroutine] There are several implementations for coroutines in Java.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] Despite the constraints imposed by Java's abstractions, the JVM does not preclude the possibility.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] There are four general methods used, but two break bytecode portability among standards-compliant JVMs.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] Since ECMAScript 2015, JavaScript has support for generators, which are a special case of coroutines.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] Kotlin implements coroutines as part of a first-party library.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] Lua has supported first-class stackful asymmetric coroutines since version 5.0 (2003), in the standard library *coroutine*.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] Modula-2 as defined by Wirth implements coroutines as part of the standard SYSTEM library.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] The procedure NEWPROCESS() fills in a context given a code block and space for a stack as parameters, and the procedure TRANSFER() transfers control to a coroutine given the coroutine's context as its parameter.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] The Mono Common Language Runtime has support for continuations, from which coroutines can be built.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] During the development of the .NET Framework 2.0, Microsoft extended the design of the Common Language Runtime (CLR) hosting APIs to handle fiber-based scheduling with an eye towards its use in fiber-mode for SQL server.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] Before release, support for the task switching hook `ICLRTask::SwitchOut` was removed due to time constraints.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] Consequently, the use of the fiber API to switch tasks is currently not a viable option in the .NET Framework.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] OCaml supports coroutines through its `Thread` module.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] These coroutines provide concurrency without parallelism, and are scheduled preemptively on a single operating system thread.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] Since OCaml 5.0, green threads are also available; provided by different modules.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] Coroutines are natively implemented in all Raku backends.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] Python has support for coroutines using the `asyncio.create_task()` function.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] Racket provides native continuations, with a trivial implementation of coroutines provided in the official package catalog.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] Since Scheme provides full support for continuations, implementing coroutines is nearly trivial, requiring only that a queue of continuations be maintained.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] Since, in most Smalltalk environments, the execution stack is a first-class citizen, coroutines can be implemented without additional library or VM support.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] Since version 8.6, Tcl supports coroutines in the core language.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] Vala implements native support for coroutines.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] They are designed to be used with a GTK Main Loop, but can be used alone if care is taken to ensure that the end callback will never have to be called before doing, at least, one yield.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] Machine-dependent assembly languages often provide direct methods for coroutine execution.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] On VAXen (in VAX MACRO) the comparable instruction is "JSB @(SP)+".
[src:simula-language/coroutine] Even on a Motorola 6809 there is the instruction "JSR [,S++]"; note the "++", as 2 bytes (of address) are popped from the stack.
[src:simula-language/coroutine] This instruction is much used in the (standard) 'monitor' Assist 09.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] A **discrete-event simulation** (**DES**) models the operation of a system as a (discrete) sequence of events in time.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] Each event occurs at a particular instant in time and marks a change of state in the system.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] Between consecutive events, no change in the system is assumed to occur; thus the simulation time can directly jump to the occurrence time of the next event, which is called **next-event time progression**.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] In addition to next-event time progression, there is also an alternative approach, called **incremental time progression**, where time is broken up into small time slices and the system state is updated according to the set of events/activities happening in the time slice.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] Because not every time slice has to be simulated, a next-event time simulation can typically run faster than a corresponding incremental time simulation.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] Both forms of DES contrast with continuous simulation in which the system state is changed continuously over time on the basis of a set of differential equations defining the rates of change for state variables.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] In the past, these three types of simulation have also been referred to, respectively, as: event scheduling simulation, activity scanning simulation, and process interaction simulation.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] It can also be noted that there are similarities between the implementation of the event queue in event scheduling, and the scheduling queue used in operating systems.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] A common exercise in learning how to build discrete-event simulations is to model a queueing system, such as customers arriving at a bank teller to be served by a clerk.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] In this example, the system objects are ***customer*** and ***teller***, while the system events are ***customer-arrival***, ***service-start*** and ***service-end***.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] When a *service-start* event occurs, the state variable *teller-status* is set to "busy" and a *service-end* follow-up event is scheduled with a delay (obtained from sampling a *service-time* random variable).
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] When a *service-end* event occurs, the state variable *queue-length* is decremented by 1 (representing the customer's departure).
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] If the state variable *queue-length* is still greater than zero, a *Service-Start* follow-up event is scheduled to happen without any delay.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] Otherwise, the state variable *teller-status* is set to "available".
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] The random variables that need to be characterized to model this system stochastically are the *interarrival-time* for recurrent *customer-arrival* events and the *service-time* for the delays of *service-end* events.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] A system state is a set of variables that captures the salient properties of the system to be studied.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] The state trajectory over time S(t) can be mathematically represented by a step function whose value can change whenever an event occurs.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] The simulation must keep track of the current simulation time, in whatever measurement units are suitable for the system being modeled.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] In discrete-event simulations, as opposed to continuous simulations, time 'hops' because events are instantaneous – the clock skips to the next event start time as the simulation proceeds.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] The simulation maintains at least one list of simulation events.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] This is sometimes called the *pending event set* because it lists events that are pending as a result of previously simulated event but have yet to be simulated themselves.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] An event is described by the time at which it occurs and a type, indicating the code that will be used to simulate that event.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] It is common for the event code to be parametrized, in which case, the event description also contains parameters to the event code.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] The event list is also referred to as the *future event list* (FEL) or *future event set* (FES).
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] When events are instantaneous, activities that extend over time are modeled as sequences of events.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] Some simulation frameworks allow the time of an event to be specified as an interval, giving the start time and the end time of each event.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] Single-threaded simulation engines based on instantaneous events have just one current event.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] In contrast, multi-threaded simulation engines and simulation engines supporting an interval-based event model may have multiple current events.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] In both cases, there are significant problems with synchronization between current events.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] The pending event set is typically organized as a priority queue, sorted by event time.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] That is, regardless of the order in which events are added to the event set, they are removed in strictly chronological order.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] Various priority queue implementations have been studied in the context of discrete event simulation; alternatives studied have included splay trees, skip lists, calendar queues, and ladder queues.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] On massively-parallel machines, such as multi-core or many-core CPUs, the pending event set can be implemented by relying on non-blocking algorithms, in order to reduce the cost of synchronization among the concurrent threads.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] Typically, events are scheduled dynamically as the simulation proceeds.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] For example, in the bank example noted above, the event CUSTOMER-ARRIVAL at time t would, if the CUSTOMER_QUEUE was empty and TELLER was idle, include the creation of the subsequent event CUSTOMER-DEPARTURE to occur at time t+s, where s is a number generated from the SERVICE-TIME distribution.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] The simulation needs to generate random variables of various kinds, depending on the system model.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] This is accomplished by one or more Pseudorandom number generators.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] The use of pseudo-random numbers as opposed to true random numbers is a benefit should a simulation need a rerun with exactly the same behavior.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] One of the problems with the random number distributions used in discrete-event simulation is that the steady-state distributions of event times may not be known in advance.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] As a result, the initial set of events placed into the pending event set will not have arrival times representative of the steady-state distribution.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] This problem is typically solved by bootstrapping the simulation model.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] Only a limited effort is made to assign realistic times to the initial set of pending events.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] These events, however, schedule additional events, and with time, the distribution of event times approaches its steady state.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] This is called *bootstrapping* the simulation model.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] In gathering statistics from the running model, it is important to either disregard events that occur before the steady state is reached or to run the simulation for long enough that the bootstrapping behavior is overwhelmed by steady-state behavior.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] (This use of the term *bootstrapping* can be contrasted with its use in both statistics and computing).
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] The simulation typically keeps track of the system's statistics, which quantify the aspects of interest.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] In the bank example, it is of interest to track the mean waiting times.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] In a simulation model, performance metrics are not analytically derived from probability distributions, but rather as averages over replications, that is different runs of the model.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] Confidence intervals are usually constructed to help assess the quality of the output.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] Because events are bootstrapped, theoretically a discrete-event simulation could run forever.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] So the simulation designer must decide when the simulation will end.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] Typical choices are "at time t" or "after processing n number of events" or, more generally, "when statistical measure X reaches the value x".
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] Pidd (1998) has proposed the three-phased approach to discrete event simulation.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] In this approach, the first phase is to jump to the next chronological event.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] The second phase is to execute all events that unconditionally occur at that time (these are called B-events).
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] The third phase is to execute all events that conditionally occur at that time (these are called C-events).
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] The three phase approach is a refinement of the event-based approach in which simultaneous events are ordered so as to make the most efficient use of computer resources.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] The three-phase approach is used by a number of commercial simulation software packages, but from the user's point of view, the specifics of the underlying simulation method are generally hidden.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] Simulation approaches are particularly well equipped to help users diagnose issues in complex environments.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] The theory of constraints illustrates the importance of understanding bottlenecks in a system.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] Identifying and removing bottlenecks allows improving processes and the overall system.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] For instance, in manufacturing enterprises bottlenecks may be created by excess inventory, overproduction, variability in processes and variability in routing or sequencing.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] By accurately documenting the system with the help of a simulation model it is possible to gain a bird’s eye view of the entire system.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] A working model of a system allows management to understand performance drivers.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] A simulation can be built to include any number of performance indicators such as worker utilization, on-time delivery rate, scrap rate, cash cycles, and so on.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] An operating theater is generally shared between several surgical disciplines.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] Through better understanding the nature of these procedures it may be possible to increase the patient throughput.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] Example: If a heart surgery takes on average four hours, changing an operating room schedule from eight available hours to nine will not increase patient throughput.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] On the other hand, if a hernia procedure takes on average twenty minutes providing an extra hour may also not yield any increased throughput if the capacity and average time spent in the recovery room is not considered.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] Many systems improvement ideas are built on sound principles, proven methodologies (Lean, Six Sigma, TQM, etc.) yet fail to improve the overall system.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] A simulation model allows the user to understand and test a performance improvement idea in the context of the overall system.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] Simulation modeling is commonly used to model potential investments.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] Through modeling investments decision-makers can make informed decisions and evaluate potential alternatives.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] Discrete event simulation is used in computer network to simulate new protocols, different system architectures (distributed, hierarchical, centralised, P2P) before actual deployment.
[src:simula-language/discrete-event-simulation] It is possible to define different evaluation metrics, such as service time, bandwidth, dropped packets, resource consumption, and so on.
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] Nygaard was born in Oslo and received his master's degree in mathematics at the University of Oslo in 1956.
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] His thesis on abstract probability theory was entitled "Theoretical Aspects of Monte Carlo methods".
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] Nygaard worked full-time at the Norwegian Defense Research Establishment from 1948 to 1960, in computing and programming (1948–1954) and operational research (1952–1960).
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] From 1957 to 1960, he was head of the first operations research groups in the Norwegian defense establishment.
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] He was cofounder and first chairman of the Norwegian Operational Research Society (1959–1964).
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] In 1960, he was hired by the Norwegian Computing Center (NCC), responsible for building up the NCC as a research institute in the 1960s, becoming its Director of Research in 1962.
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] The languages introduced the core concepts of object-oriented programming: objects, classes, inheritance, virtual quantities, and multi-threaded (quasi-parallel) program execution.
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] In 2004, the Association Internationale pour les Technologies Objets (AITO) established an annual prize in the name of Ole-Johan Dahl and Kristen Nygaard to honor their pioneering work on object-orientation.
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] This Dahl–Nygaard Prize is awarded annually to two individuals that have made significant technical contributions to the field of object-orientation.
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] The work should be in the spirit of the pioneer conceptual and/or implementation work of Dahl and Nygaard which shaped the present view of object-oriented programming.
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] The prize is presented each year at the ECOOP conference.
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] The prize consists of two awards given to a senior and a junior professional.
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] He conducted research for Norwegian trade unions on planning, control, and data processing, all evaluated in light of the objectives of organised labour (1971–1973), working together with Olav Terje Bergo.
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] His other research and development work included the social impact of computer technology, and the general system description language DELTA (1973–1975), working with Erik Holbaek-Hanssen and Petter Haandlykken.
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] Nygaard was a professor at Aarhus University, Denmark (1975–1976) and then became professor emeritus at the University of Oslo (part-time from 1977, full-time 1984–1996).
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] His work in Aarhus and Oslo included research and education in system development and the social impact of computer technology, and became the foundation of the Scandinavian School in System Development, which is closely linked to the field of participatory design.
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] Starting in 1976, he was engaged in developing and (since 1986) implementing the general object-oriented programming language BETA, together with Bent Bruun Kristensen, Ole Lehrmann Madsen, and Birger Møller-Pedersen.
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] The language is now available on a wide range of computers.
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] Also in the 1980s, he was chairman of the steering committee for the Cost-13 (European Common Market Commission)-financed research project on the extensions of profession-oriented languages necessary when artificial intelligence and information technology are becoming part of professional work.
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] Nygaard's research from 1995 to 1999 was related to distributed systems.
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] The GOODS team also included Haakon Bryhni, Dag Sjøberg, and Ole Smørdal.
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] Nygaard's final research interests were studies of the introductory teaching of programming, and creating a process-oriented conceptual platform for informatics.
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] These subjects are to be developed in a new research project named Comprehensive Object-Oriented Learning (COOL), together with several international test sites.
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] He was giving lectures and courses on these subjects in Norway and elsewhere.
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] In November 1999, he became chair of an advisory committee on Broadband Communication for the Norwegian Department for Municipal and Regional Affairs.
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] He held a part-time position at Simula Research Laboratory from 2001, when the research institute was opened.
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] In June 1990, he received an honorary doctorate from Lund University, Sweden.
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] In June 1991, he became the first individual to be given an honorary doctorate by Aalborg University, Denmark.
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] He became a member of the Norwegian Academy of Sciences.
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] In October 1990, Computer Professionals for Social Responsibility awarded him its Norbert Wiener Award for Social and Professional Responsibility.
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] In 1999, he and Dahl became the first people to receive the then new Rosing Prize, awarded by the Norwegian Data Association for exceptional professional achievements.
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] In June 2000, he was awarded an Honorary Fellowship for "his originating of object technology concepts" by the Object Management Group, a technical standards group for object-orientation, which maintains several International Organization for Standardization (ISO) standards.
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] In November 2001, the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE) awarded Nygaard and Dahl the IEEE John von Neumann Medal "For the introduction of the concepts underlying object-oriented programming through the design and implementation of Simula 67".
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] In February 2002, he was given, once more with Ole-Johan Dahl, the 2001 A.
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] In August 2000, he was made Commander of the Royal Norwegian Order of St.
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] In 1984 and 1985, Nygaard was chairman of the Informatics Committee of the University of Oslo, and active in the design of the university's plan for developing research, education and computing and communication facilities at all faculties of the university.
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] He was the first chairman of the Environment Protection Committee of the Norwegian Association for the Protection of Nature.
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] He was for 10 years (in the 1970s) Norwegian representative in the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) activities on information technology.
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] He has been a member of the Research Committee of the Norwegian Federation of Trade Unions, and cooperated with unions in many countries.
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] For several years, he was engaged in running an experimental social institution trying new ways to create humane living conditions for socially outcast alcoholics.
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] Nygaard was active in Norwegian politics.
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] In the mid and late 1960s, he was a member of the National Executive Committee of the Norwegian Liberal Party, and chair of that party's Strategy Committee.
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] He was a minor ballot candidate in the 1949 parliamentary election.
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] During the intense political fight before the 1972 referendum on whether Norway should become a member of the European Common Market (later the European Union), he worked as coordinator for the many youth organisations that worked against membership.
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] From 1971 to 2001, Nygaard was a member of the Labour Party, and a member of their committees on research policies.
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] In November 1988, he became chair of the Information Committee on Norway and the EEC, in August 1990 reorganized as *Nei til EF* an organization disseminating information about Norway's relation to the Common Market, and coordinating the efforts to keep Norway outside.
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] (No to European Union membership for Norway, literally "No to the EU").
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] In 1993, when the EEC ratified the Maastricht Treaty and became the European Union the organization changed its name to reflect this.
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] *Nei til EF* became the largest political organization in Norway (145,000 members in 1994, from a population of 4 million).
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] Nygaard worked with Anne Enger Lahnstein, leader of the anti-EU Centre Party, in this campaign.
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] In the referendum on 28 November 1994, "Nei til EU" succeeded: 52.2% of the electorate voted "No", and the voter participation was the highest ever in Norway's history: 88.8%.
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] The strategy of the campaign, insisted by Nygaard, was that it had to be *for* something as well as against, i.e., the Scandinavian welfare state Nygaard considered threatened by the Maastricht Agreement.
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] He resigned as chair in 1995, and was later the chair of the organization's strategy committee and a member of its council.
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] The European Alliance of EU-critical Movements (TEAM) was successfully started 3 March 1997.
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] Kristen Nygaard married Johanna Nygaard in 1951.
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] She worked at the Norwegian Agency for Aid to Developing Countries.
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] She specialized for a number of years in recruiting and giving administrative support to specialists working in East Africa.
[src:simula-language/kristen-nygaard] Johanna and Kristen Nygaard had three children and seven grandchildren.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Notable languages with OOP support include Ada, ActionScript, C++, Common Lisp, C#, Dart, Eiffel, Fortran 2003, Haxe, Java, JavaScript, Kotlin, Logo, MATLAB, Objective-C, Object Pascal, Perl, PHP, Python, R, Raku, Ruby, Scala, SIMSCRIPT, Simula, Smalltalk, Swift, Vala and Visual Basic (.NET).
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] The idea of "objects" in programming began with the artificial intelligence group at Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT) in the late 1950s and early 1960s.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Here, "object" referred to LISP atoms with identified properties (attributes).
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Another early example was Sketchpad created by Ivan Sutherland at MIT in 1960–1961.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] In the glossary of his technical report, Sutherland defined terms like "object" and "instance" (with the class concept covered by "master" or "definition"), albeit specialized to graphical interaction.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Later, in 1968, AED-0, MIT's version of the ALGOL programming language, connected data structures ("plexes") and procedures, prefiguring what were later termed "messages", "methods", and "member functions".
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Topics such as data abstraction and modular programming were common points of discussion at this time.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Meanwhile, in Norway, Simula was developed during the years 1961–1967.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Simula introduced essential object-oriented ideas, such as classes, inheritance, and dynamic binding.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Simula was used mainly by researchers involved with physical modelling, like the movement of ships and their content through cargo ports.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Simula is generally accepted as being the first language with the primary features and framework of an object-oriented language.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Influenced by both MIT and Simula, Alan Kay began developing his own ideas in November 1966.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] He would go on to create Smalltalk, an influential OOP language.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] By 1967, Kay was already using the term "object-oriented programming" in conversation.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Although sometimes called the "father" of OOP, Kay has said his ideas differ from how OOP is commonly understood, and has implied that the computer science establishment did not adopt his notion.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] A 1976 MIT memo co-authored by Barbara Liskov lists Simula 67, CLU, and Alphard as object-oriented languages, but does not mention Smalltalk.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] In the 1970s, the first version of the Smalltalk programming language was developed at Xerox PARC by Alan Kay, Dan Ingalls and Adele Goldberg.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Smalltalk-72 was notable for use of objects at the language level and its graphical development environment.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Smalltalk was a fully dynamic system, allowing users to create and modify classes as they worked.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Much of the theory of OOP was developed in the context of Smalltalk, for example multiple inheritance.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] In the late 1970s and 1980s, OOP rose to prominence.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] The Flavors object-oriented Lisp was developed starting 1979, introducing multiple inheritance and mixins.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] In August 1981, Byte Magazine highlighted Smalltalk and OOP, introducing these ideas to a wide audience.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] LOOPS, the object system for Interlisp-D, was influenced by Smalltalk and Flavors, and a paper about it was published in 1982.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] In 1986, the first *Conference on Object-Oriented Programming, Systems, Languages, and Applications* (OOPSLA) was attended by 1,000 people.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] This conference marked the start of efforts to consolidate Lisp object systems, eventually resulting in the Common Lisp Object System.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] In the 1980s, there were a few attempts to design processor architectures that included hardware support for objects in memory, but these were not successful.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Examples include the Intel iAPX 432 and the Linn Smart Rekursiv.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] In the mid-1980s, new object-oriented languages like Objective-C, C++, and the Eiffel language emerged.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Objective-C was developed by Brad Cox, who had used Smalltalk at ITT Inc.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Bjarne Stroustrup created C++ based on his experience using Simula for his PhD thesis.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Bertrand Meyer produced the first design of the Eiffel language in 1985, which focused on software quality using a design by contract approach.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] In the 1990s, OOP became the main way of programming, especially as more languages supported it.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] These included Visual FoxPro 3.0, C++, and Delphi.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] OOP became even more popular with the rise of graphical user interfaces, which used objects for buttons, menus and other elements.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] One well-known example is Apple's Cocoa framework, used on macOS and written in Objective-C.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] OOP toolkits also enhanced the popularity of event-driven programming.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] At ETH Zürich, Niklaus Wirth and his colleagues created new approaches to OOP.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Modula-2 (1978) and Oberon (1987), included a distinctive approach to object orientation, classes, and type checking across module boundaries.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Inheritance is not obvious in Wirth's design since his nomenclature looks in the opposite direction: It is called type extension and the viewpoint is from the parent down to the inheritor.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Many programming languages that were initially developed before OOP was popular have been augmented with object-oriented features, including Ada, BASIC, Fortran, Pascal, and COBOL.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] The OOP features provided by languages vary.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Below are some common features of OOP languages.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Comparing OOP with other styles, like relational programming, is difficult because there isn't a clear, agreed-upon definition of OOP.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Some programming languages, like Java, provide information hiding via visibility key words (`private` and `public`).
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Some languages like Python don't provide a visibility feature, but developers might follow a convention such as starting a private member name with an underscore.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Intermediate levels of access also exist, such as Java's `protected` keyword, (which allows access from the same class and its subclasses, but not objects of a different class), and the `internal` keyword in C#, Swift, and Kotlin, which restricts access to files within the same module.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Supporters of information hiding and data abstraction say it makes code easier to reuse and intuitively represents real-world situations.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] However, others argue that OOP does not enhance readability or modularity.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Raymond has written that OOP languages tend to encourage thickly layered programs that destroy transparency.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Raymond compares this unfavourably to the approach taken with Unix and the C language.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] SOLID includes the open/closed principle, which says that classes and functions should be "open for extension, but closed for modification".
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Luca Cardelli has stated that OOP languages have "extremely poor modularity properties with respect to class extension and modification", and tend to be extremely complex.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Leo Brodie says that information hiding can lead to duplicate code, which goes against the don't repeat yourself rule of software development.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Inheritance can be supported via the class or the prototype, which have differences but use similar terms like object and instance.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] In class-based programming, the most common type of OOP, an object is an instance of a class.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] The class defines the data (variables) and methods (logic).
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] An object is created via the constructor.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Every instance of the class has the same set of variables and methods.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Classes may inherit from other classes, creating a hierarchy of classes: a case of a subclass inheriting from a super-class.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] For example, an `Employee` class might inherit from a `Person` class which endows the Employee object with the variables from `Person`.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] The subclass may add variables and methods that do not affect the super-class.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Most languages also allow the subclass to override super-class methods.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Some languages support multiple inheritance, where a class can inherit from more than one class, and other languages similarly support mixins or traits.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] For example, a mixin called UnicodeConversionMixin might add a method unicode_to_ascii() to both a FileReader and a WebPageScraper class.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] An abstract class cannot be directly instantiated as an object.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Other classes are utility classes which contain only class variables and methods and are not meant to be instantiated or subclassed.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Instead of providing a class concept, in prototype-based programming, an object is linked to another object, called its *prototype* or *parent*.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] In Self, an object may have multiple or no parents, but in the most popular prototype-based language, JavaScript, an object has exactly one prototype link, up to the base object whose prototype is null.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] A prototype acts as a model for new objects.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] For example, if you have an object `fruit`, you can make two objects `apple` and `orange` that share traits of the `fruit` prototype.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Prototype-based languages also allow objects to have their own unique properties, so the `apple` object might have an attribute `sugar_content`, while the `orange` or `fruit` objects do not.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] In all OOP languages, via object composition, an object can contain other objects.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] For example, an `Employee` object might contain an `Address` object, along with other information like `name` and `position`.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Composition is a "has-a" relationships, like "an employee has an address".
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Some languages, like Go, don't support inheritance.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Instead, they encourage "composition over inheritance", where objects are built using smaller parts instead of parent-child relationships.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] For example, instead of inheriting from class Person, the Employee class could simply contain a Person object.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] This lets the Employee class control how much of Person it exposes to other parts of the program.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Delegation is another language feature that can be used as an alternative to inheritance.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Programmers have different opinions on inheritance.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Bjarne Stroustrup, author of C++, has stated that it is possible to do OOP without inheritance.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Rob Pike has criticized inheritance for creating complex hierarchies instead of simpler solutions.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] People often think that if one class inherits from another, it means the subclass "is a" more specific version of the original class.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] This presumes the program semantics are that objects from the subclass can always replace objects from the original class without problems.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] This concept is known as behavioral subtyping, more specifically the Liskov substitution principle.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] However, this is often not true, especially in programming languages that allow mutable objects, objects that change after they are created.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] In fact, subtype polymorphism as enforced by the type checker in OOP languages cannot guarantee behavioral subtyping in most if not all contexts.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] For example, the circle-ellipse problem is notoriously difficult to handle using OOP's concept of inheritance.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Behavioral subtyping is undecidable in general, so it cannot be easily implemented by a compiler.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Because of this, programmers must carefully design class hierarchies to avoid mistakes that the programming language itself cannot catch.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] A method may be invoked via dynamic dispatch such that the method is selected at runtime instead of compile time.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] If the method choice depends on more than one type of object (such as other objects passed as parameters), it's called multiple dispatch.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] In this context, a method call is also known as message passing, meaning the method name and its inputs are like a message sent to the object for it to act on.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Dynamic dispatch works together with inheritance: if an object doesn't have the requested method, it looks up to its parent class (delegation), and continues up the chain to find a matching method.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Polymorphism in OOP refers to subtyping or subtype polymorphism, where a function can work with a specific interface and thus manipulate entities of different classes in a uniform manner.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] For example, imagine a program has two shapes: a circle and a square.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Both come from a common class called "Shape." Each shape has its own way of drawing itself.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] With subtype polymorphism, the program doesn't need to know the type of each shape, and can simply call the "Draw" method for each shape.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] The programming language runtime will ensure the correct version of the "Draw" method runs for each shape.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Because the details of each shape are handled inside their own classes, this makes the code simpler and more organized, enabling strong separation of concerns.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] An object's methods can access the object's data.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Many programming languages use a special word, like `this` or `self`, to refer to the current object.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] In languages that support open recursion, a method in an object can call other methods in the same object, including itself, using this special word.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] This allows a method in one class to call another method defined later in a subclass, a feature known as late binding.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Design patterns are common solutions to problems in software design.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Some design patterns are especially useful for OOP, and design patterns are typically introduced in an OOP context.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Sometimes, objects represent real-world things and processes in digital form.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] For example, a graphics program may have objects such as `circle`, `square`, and `menu`.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] An online shopping system might have objects such as `shopping cart`, `customer`, and `product`.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Niklaus Wirth said, "This paradigm [OOP] closely reflects the structure of systems in the real world and is therefore well suited to model complex systems with complex behavior".
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] However, more often, objects represent abstract entities, like an open file or a unit converter.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Not everyone agrees that OOP makes it easy to copy the real world exactly or that doing so is even necessary.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Bob Martin suggests that because classes are software, their relationships don't match the real-world relationships they represent.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Bertrand Meyer argues that a program is not a model of the world but a model of some part of the world; "Reality is a cousin twice removed".
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Steve Yegge noted that natural languages lack the OOP approach of naming a thing (object) before an action (method), as opposed to functional programming which does the reverse.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] This can make an OOP solution more complex than one written via procedural programming.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] The following are notable software design patterns for OOP objects.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] A common anti-pattern is the God object, an object that knows or does too much.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Both OOP and relational database management systems (RDBMSs) are widely used in software today.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] However, relational databases don't store objects directly, which creates a challenge when using them together.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] This issue is called object-relational impedance mismatch.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] To solve this problem, developers use different methods, but none of them are perfect.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] One of the most common solutions is object-relational mapping (ORM), which helps connect object-oriented programs to relational databases.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Examples of ORM tools include Visual FoxPro, Java Data Objects, and Ruby on Rails ActiveRecord.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Some databases, called object databases, are designed to work with OOP.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] However, they have not been as popular or successful as relational databases.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Date and Darwen have proposed a theoretical foundation that uses OOP as a kind of customizable type system to support RDBMSs, but it forbids objects containing pointers to other objects.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] In responsibility-driven design, classes are built around what they need to do and the information they share, in the form of a contract.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] This is different from data-driven design, where classes are built based on the data they need to store.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] According to Wirfs-Brock and Wilkerson, the originators of responsibility-driven design, responsibility-driven design is the better approach.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Researchers have tried to formally define the semantics of OOP.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Inheritance presents difficulties, particularly with the interactions between open recursion and encapsulated state.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Researchers have used recursive types and co-algebraic data types to incorporate essential features of OOP.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Abadi and Cardelli defined several extensions of System F<: that deal with mutable objects, allowing both subtype polymorphism and parametric polymorphism (generics), and were able to formally model many OOP concepts and constructs.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Although far from trivial, static analysis of object-oriented programming languages such as Java is a mature field, with several commercial tools.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Many popular programming languages, like C++, Java, and Python, use OOP.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] In the past, OOP was widely accepted, but recently, some programmers have criticized it and prefer functional programming instead.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] A study by Potok et al. found no major difference in productivity between OOP and procedural programming.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Some believe that OOP places too much focus on using objects rather than on algorithms and data structures.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] For example, programmer Rob Pike pointed out that OOP can make programmers think more about type hierarchy than composition.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] He has called OOP "the Roman numerals of computing".
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Rich Hickey, creator of Clojure, described OOP as overly simplistic, especially when it comes to representing real-world things that change over time.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Alexander Stepanov said that OOP tries to fit everything into a single type, which can be limiting.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] He argued that sometimes we need multisorted algebras: families of interfaces that span multiple types, such as in generic programming.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Stepanov also said that calling everything an "object" doesn't add much understanding.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] OOP was created to make code easier to reuse and maintain.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] However, it was not designed to clearly show the flow of a program's instructions.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] As computers began using more parallel processing and multiple threads, it became more important to understand and control how instructions flow.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Paul Graham believes big companies like OOP because it helps manage large teams of average programmers.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] He argues that OOP adds structure, making it harder for one person to make serious mistakes, but at the same time restrains smart programmers.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Raymond, a Unix programmer and open-source software advocate, argues that OOP is not the best way to write programs.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Richard Feldman says that, while OOP features helped some languages stay organized, their popularity comes from other reasons.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Lawrence Krubner argues that OOP doesn't offer special advantages compared to other styles, like functional programming, and can complicate coding.
[src:simula-language/object-oriented-programming] Luca Cardelli says that OOP is slower and takes longer to compile than procedural programming.
[src:simula-language/ole-johan-dahl] He was the son of Finn Dahl (1898–1962) and Ingrid Othilie Kathinka Pedersen (1905–80).
[src:simula-language/ole-johan-dahl] When he was seven, his family moved to Drammen.
[src:simula-language/ole-johan-dahl] When he was thirteen, the whole family fled to Sweden during the German occupation of Norway in World War II.
[src:simula-language/ole-johan-dahl] After the war's end, Dahl studied numerical mathematics at the University of Oslo.
[src:simula-language/ole-johan-dahl] Dahl became a full professor at the University of Oslo in 1968 and was a gifted teacher as well as researcher.
[src:simula-language/ole-johan-dahl] Here he worked on *Hierarchical Program Structures*, probably his most influential publication, which appeared co-authored with C.A.R.
[src:simula-language/ole-johan-dahl] Hoare in the influential book *Structured Programming* of 1972 by Dahl, Edsger Dijkstra, and Hoare, perhaps the best-known academic book concerning software in the 1970s.
[src:simula-language/ole-johan-dahl] As his career advanced, Dahl grew increasingly interested in the use of formal methods, to rigorously reason about object-orientation for example.
[src:simula-language/ole-johan-dahl] His expertise ranged from the practical application of ideas to their formal mathematical underpinning to ensure the validity of the approach.
[src:simula-language/ole-johan-dahl] Dahl is widely accepted as Norway's foremost computer scientist.
[src:simula-language/ole-johan-dahl] Dahl and Nygaard were the first to develop the concepts of class, subclass (allowing implicit information hiding), inheritance, dynamic object creation, etc., all important aspects of the OO paradigm.
[src:simula-language/ole-johan-dahl] An *object* is a self-contained component (with a data structure and associated procedures or *methods*) in a software system.
[src:simula-language/ole-johan-dahl] These are combined to form a complete system.
[src:simula-language/ole-johan-dahl] The object-oriented approach is now pervasive in modern software development, including widely used imperative programming languages such as C++ and Java.
[src:simula-language/ole-johan-dahl] He received the Turing Award for his work in 2001 (with Kristen Nygaard).
[src:simula-language/ole-johan-dahl] He received the 2002 Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE) John von Neumann Medal (with Kristen Nygaard) and was named Commander of the Royal Norwegian Order of St.
[src:simula-language/ole-johan-dahl] The Association Internationale pour les Technologies Objets named the Dahl-Nygaard Prize after Dahl.
[src:simula-language/simula] Simula 67 introduced objects, classes, inheritance and subclasses, virtual procedures, coroutines, and discrete event simulation, and featured garbage collection.
[src:simula-language/simula] Other forms of subtyping (besides inheriting subclasses) were introduced in Simula derivatives.
[src:simula-language/simula] Simula is considered the first object-oriented programming language.
[src:simula-language/simula] As its name suggests, the first Simula version by 1962 was designed for doing simulations; Simula 67 though was designed to be a general-purpose programming language and provided the framework for many of the features of object-oriented languages today.
[src:simula-language/simula] Simula has been used in a wide range of applications such as simulating very-large-scale integration (VLSI) designs, process modeling, communication protocols, algorithms, and other applications such as typesetting, computer graphics, and education.
[src:simula-language/simula] Computer scientists such as Bjarne Stroustrup, creator of C++, and James Gosling, creator of Java, have acknowledged Simula as a major influence.
[src:simula-language/simula] Simula-type objects are reimplemented in C++, Object Pascal, Java, C#, and many other languages.
[src:simula-language/simula] The following account is based on Jan Rune Holmevik's historical essay.
[src:simula-language/simula] Kristen Nygaard started writing computer simulation programs in 1957.
[src:simula-language/simula] Nygaard saw a need for a better way to describe the heterogeneity and the operation of a system.
[src:simula-language/simula] To further develop his ideas for a computer language to describe a system, Nygaard realized that he needed someone with more computer programming skills than he had.
[src:simula-language/simula] Ole-Johan Dahl joined him on his work in January 1962.
[src:simula-language/simula] Shortly after, the decision was made to link the language to ALGOL 60.
[src:simula-language/simula] By May 1962, the main concepts for a simulation language were established; *SIMULA I*, a specialized programming language designed for simulating discrete event systems, was born.
[src:simula-language/simula] Kristen Nygaard was invited to visit the Eckert–Mauchly Computer Corporation in late May 1962 in connection with the marketing of their new UNIVAC 1107 computer.
[src:simula-language/simula] At that visit, Nygaard presented the ideas of Simula to Robert Bemer, the director of systems programming at Univac.
[src:simula-language/simula] Bemer was a great ALGOL fan and found the Simula project compelling.
[src:simula-language/simula] Bemer was also chairperson of a session at the second international conference on information processing hosted by International Federation for Information Processing (IFIP).
[src:simula-language/simula] He invited Nygaard, who presented the paper "SIMULA – An Extension of ALGOL to the Description of Discrete-Event Networks".
[src:simula-language/simula] The Norwegian Computing Center got a UNIVAC 1107 in August 1963 at a considerable discount, on which Dahl implemented the SIMULA I under contract with UNIVAC.
[src:simula-language/simula] The implementation was based on the UNIVAC ALGOL 60 compiler.
[src:simula-language/simula] SIMULA I was fully operational on the UNIVAC 1107 by January 1965.
[src:simula-language/simula] In the following few years, Dahl and Nygaard spent a lot of time teaching Simula.
[src:simula-language/simula] Simula spread to several countries around the world and SIMULA I was later implemented on other computers including the Burroughs B5500 and the Russian Ural-16.
[src:simula-language/simula] Hoare introduced the concept of record class construct, which Dahl and Nygaard extended with the concept of prefixing and other features to meet their requirements for a generalized process concept.
[src:simula-language/simula] Dahl and Nygaard presented their paper on class and subclass declarations at the IFIP Working Conference on simulation languages in Oslo, May 1967.
[src:simula-language/simula] This paper became the first formal definition of Simula 67.
[src:simula-language/simula] In June 1967, a conference was held to standardize the language and initiate a number of implementations.
[src:simula-language/simula] Dahl proposed to unify the type and the class concept.
[src:simula-language/simula] This led to serious discussions, and the proposal was rejected by the board.
[src:simula-language/simula] Simula 67 was formally standardized on the first meeting of the Simula Standards Group (SSG) in February 1968.
[src:simula-language/simula] Simula was influential in the development of Smalltalk and later object-oriented programming languages.
[src:simula-language/simula] It also helped inspire the actor model of concurrent computation although Simula only supports coroutines and not true concurrency.
[src:simula-language/simula] These implementations were ported to a wide range of platforms.
[src:simula-language/simula] The TOPS-10 implemented the concept of public, protected, and private member variables and procedures, that later was integrated into Simula Standard in 1986.
[src:simula-language/simula] Simula Standard 1986 is the latest standard and is ported to a wide range of platforms.
[src:simula-language/simula] In November 2001, Dahl and Nygaard were awarded the IEEE John von Neumann Medal by the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers "For the introduction of the concepts underlying object-oriented programming through the design and implementation of SIMULA 67".
[src:simula-language/simula] In April 2002, they received the 2001 A.
[src:simula-language/simula] Simula Research Laboratory is a research institute named after the Simula language, and Nygaard held a part-time position there from the opening in 2001.
[src:simula-language/simula] The new Computer Science building at the University of Oslo is named Ole Johan Dahl's House, in Dahl's honour, and the main auditorium is named Simula.
[src:simula-language/simula] The empty computer file is the minimal program in Simula, measured by the size of the source code.
[src:simula-language/simula] It consists of one thing only; a dummy statement.
[src:simula-language/simula] It begins executing and immediately terminates.
[src:simula-language/simula] The language lacks any return value from the program.
[src:simula-language/simula] The above example has one super class (Glyph) with two subclasses (`Char` and `Line`).
[src:simula-language/simula] There is one virtual procedure with two implementations.
[src:simula-language/simula] The execution starts by executing the main program.
[src:simula-language/simula] Simula lacks the concept of abstract classes, since classes with pure virtual procedures can be instantiated.
[src:simula-language/simula] This means that in the above example, all classes can be instantiated.
[src:simula-language/simula] Calling a pure virtual procedure will however produce a run-time error.
[src:simula-language/simula] Simula supports call by name so the Jensen's Device can easily be implemented.
[src:simula-language/simula] However, the default transmission mode for simple parameter is call by value, contrary to ALGOL which used call by name.
[src:simula-language/simula] The source code for the Jensen's Device must therefore specify call by name for the parameters when compiled by a Simula compiler.
[src:simula-language/simula] The above code uses call by name for the controlling variable (`k`) and the expression (`u`).
[src:simula-language/simula] This allows the controlling variable to be used in the expression.
[src:simula-language/simula] Note that the Simula standard allows for certain restrictions on the controlling variable in a for loop.
[src:simula-language/simula] The above code therefore uses a while loop for maximum portability.
[src:simula-language/simula] Simula includes a simulation package for doing discrete event simulations.
[src:simula-language/simula] This simulation package is based on Simula's object-oriented features and its coroutine concept.
[src:simula-language/simula] Simula provided functions to do random number generation of pseudo-random numbers.
[src:simula-language/simula] Sam, Sally, and Andy are shopping for clothes.
[src:simula-language/simula] Each one of them is browsing the store for about 12 minutes and then uses the fitting room exclusively for about three minutes, each following a normal distribution.
[src:simula-language/simula] The main block is prefixed with `Simulation` for enabling simulation.
[src:simula-language/simula] The simulation package can be used on any block and simulations can even be nested when simulating someone doing simulations.
[src:simula-language/simula] The fitting room object uses a queue (`door`) for getting access to the fitting room.
[src:simula-language/simula] When someone requests the fitting room and it's in use they must wait in this queue (`Wait (door)`).
[src:simula-language/simula] When someone leaves the fitting room the first one (if any) is released from the queue (`**Activate** door.first`) and accordingly removed from the door queue (`door.First.Out`).
[src:simula-language/simula] Person is a subclass of `Process` and its activity is described using hold (time for browsing the store and time spent in the fitting room) and calls procedures in the fitting room object for requesting and leaving the fitting room.
[src:simula-language/simula] The main program creates all the objects and activates all the person objects to put them into the event queue.
[src:simula-language/simula] The main program holds for 100 minutes of simulated time before the program terminates.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] A **simulation** is an imitative representation of a process or system that could exist in the real world.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] In this broad sense, simulation can often be used interchangeably with model.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Sometimes a clear distinction between the two terms is made, in which simulations require the use of models; the model represents the key characteristics or behaviors of the selected system or process, whereas the simulation represents the evolution of the model over time.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Another way to distinguish between the terms is to define simulation as experimentation with the help of a model.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] This definition includes time-independent simulations.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Often, computers are used to execute the simulation.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Simulation is used in many contexts, such as simulation of technology for performance tuning or optimizing, safety engineering, testing, training, education, and video games.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Simulation is also used with scientific modelling of natural systems or human systems to gain insight into their functioning, as in economics.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Simulation can be used to show the eventual real effects of alternative conditions and courses of action.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Simulation is also used when the real system cannot be engaged, because it may not be accessible, or it may be dangerous or unacceptable to engage, or it is being designed but not yet built, or it may simply not exist.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Procedures and protocols for model verification and validation are an ongoing field of academic study, refinement, research and development in simulations technology or practice, particularly in the work of computer simulation.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Historically, simulations used in different fields developed largely independently, but 20th-century studies of systems theory and cybernetics combined with the spreading use of computers across all those fields have led to some unification and a more systematic view of the concept.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] A *stand-alone simulation* is a simulation running on a single workstation by itself.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] A **distributed simulation** is one which uses more than one computer simultaneously, to guarantee access from/to different resources (e.g. multi-users operating different systems, or distributed data sets); a classical example is Distributed Interactive Simulation (DIS).
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] A *synthetic environment* is a computer simulation that can be included in human-in-the-loop simulations.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Data simulation creates artificial data to replicate the behavior of real-world data.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] The artificial data is generated using computer models or programs based on specific rules, patterns, or characteristics.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] This type of data is designed to imitate the operations of real systems, processes, or behaviors, enabling researchers and analysts to study and test scenarios without directly observing or collecting information from the real world.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] A computer simulation (or "sim") is an attempt to model a real-life or hypothetical situation on a computer so that it can be studied to see how the system works.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] By changing variables in the simulation, predictions may be made about the behaviour of the system.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] It is a tool to virtually investigate the behaviour of the system under study.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Computer simulation has become a useful part of modeling many natural systems in physics, chemistry and biology, and human systems in economics and social science (e.g., computational sociology) as well as in engineering to gain insight into the operation of those systems.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] A good example of the usefulness of using computers to simulate can be found in the field of network traffic simulation.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] In such simulations, the model behaviour will change each simulation according to the set of initial parameters assumed for the environment.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Traditionally, the formal modeling of systems has been via a mathematical model, which attempts to find analytical solutions enabling the prediction of the behaviour of the system from a set of parameters and initial conditions.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Computer simulation is often used as an adjunct to, or substitution for, modeling systems for which simple closed form analytic solutions are not possible.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] There are many different types of computer simulation, the common feature they all share is the attempt to generate a sample of representative scenarios for a model in which a complete enumeration of all possible states would be prohibitive or impossible.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Several software packages exist for running computer-based simulation modeling (e.g.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Monte Carlo simulation, stochastic modeling, multimethod modeling) that makes all the modeling almost effortless.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Modern usage of the term "computer simulation" may encompass virtually any computer-based representation.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] The computer simulates the subject machine.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Accordingly, in theoretical computer science the term *simulation* is a relation between state transition systems, useful in the study of operational semantics.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Less theoretically, an interesting application of computer simulation is to simulate computers using computers.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] For example, simulators have been used to debug a microprogram or sometimes commercial application programs, before the program is downloaded to the target machine.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Since the operation of the computer is simulated, all of the information about the computer's operation is directly available to the programmer, and the speed and execution of the simulation can be varied at will.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Simulators may also be used to interpret fault trees, or test VLSI logic designs before they are constructed.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Symbolic simulation uses variables to stand for unknown values.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] In the field of optimization, simulations of physical processes are often used in conjunction with evolutionary computation to optimize control strategies.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Simulation is extensively used for educational purposes.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] It is used for cases where it is prohibitively expensive or simply too dangerous to allow trainees to use the real equipment in the real world.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] In such situations they will spend time learning valuable lessons in a "safe" virtual environment yet living a lifelike experience (or at least it is the goal).
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Often the convenience is to permit mistakes during training for a safety-critical system.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Simulations in education are somewhat like training simulations.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] The term 'microworld' is used to refer to educational simulations which model some abstract concept rather than simulating a realistic object or environment, or in some cases model a real-world environment in a simplistic way so as to help a learner develop an understanding of the key concepts.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Normally, a user can create some sort of construction within the microworld that will behave in a way consistent with the concepts being modeled.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Seymour Papert was one of the first to advocate the value of microworlds, and the Logo programming environment developed by Papert is one of the most well-known microworlds.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Project management simulation is increasingly used to train students and professionals in the art and science of project management.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Using simulation for project management training improves learning retention and enhances the learning process.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] In recent years, there has been increasing use of social simulations for staff training in aid and development agencies.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] The Carana simulation, for example, was first developed by the United Nations Development Programme, and is now used in a very revised form by the World Bank for training staff to deal with fragile and conflict-affected countries.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Military uses for simulation often involve aircraft or armoured fighting vehicles, but can also target small arms and other weapon systems training.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Specifically, virtual firearms ranges have become the norm in most military training processes and there is a significant amount of data to suggest this is a useful tool for armed professionals.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] A **virtual simulation** is a category of simulation that uses simulation equipment to create a **simulated world** for the user.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Virtual simulations allow users to interact with a virtual world.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Virtual worlds operate on platforms of integrated software and hardware components.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] In this manner, the system can accept input from the user (e.g., body tracking, voice/sound recognition, physical controllers) and produce output to the user (e.g., visual display, aural display, haptic display) .
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Virtual simulations use the aforementioned modes of interaction to produce a sense of immersion for the user.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] There is a wide variety of input hardware available to accept user input for virtual simulations.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Research in future input systems holds a great deal of promise for virtual simulations.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Systems such as brain–computer interfaces (BCIs) offer the ability to further increase the level of immersion for virtual simulation users.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Lee, Keinrath, Scherer, Bischof, Pfurtscheller proved that naïve subjects could be trained to use a BCI to navigate a virtual apartment with relative ease.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Using the BCI, the authors found that subjects were able to freely navigate the virtual environment with relatively minimal effort.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] It is possible that these types of systems will become standard input modalities in future virtual simulation systems.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] There is a wide variety of output hardware available to deliver stimuli to users in virtual simulations.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Many medical simulators involve a computer connected to a plastic simulation of the relevant anatomy.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Sophisticated simulators of this type employ a life-size mannequin that responds to injected drugs and can be programmed to create simulations of life-threatening emergencies.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] In other simulations, visual components of the procedure are reproduced by computer graphics techniques, while touch-based components are reproduced by haptic feedback devices combined with physical simulation routines computed in response to the user's actions.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Medical simulations of this sort will often use 3D CT or MRI scans of patient data to enhance realism.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Some medical simulations are developed to be widely distributed (such as web-enabled simulations and procedural simulations that can be viewed via standard web browsers) and can be interacted with using standard computer interfaces, such as the keyboard and mouse.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] An important medical application of a simulator—although, perhaps, denoting a slightly different meaning of *simulator*—is the use of a placebo drug, a formulation that simulates the active drug in trials of drug efficacy.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Patient safety is a concern in the medical industry.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Patients have been known to suffer injuries and even death due to management error, and lack of using best standards of care and training.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Simulation is being used to study patient safety, as well as train medical professionals.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Studying patient safety and safety interventions in healthcare is challenging, because there is a lack of experimental control (i.e., patient complexity, system/process variances) to see if an intervention made a meaningful difference (Groves & Manges, 2017).
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] An example of innovative simulation to study patient safety is from nursing research.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] (2016) used a high-fidelity simulation to examine nursing safety-oriented behaviors during times such as change-of-shift report.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] However, the value of simulation interventions to translating to clinical practice are is still debatable.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] As Nishisaki states, "there is good evidence that simulation training improves provider and team self-efficacy and competence on manikins.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] There is also good evidence that procedural simulation improves actual operational performance in clinical settings." However, there is a need to have improved evidence to show that crew resource management training through simulation.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] One of the largest challenges is showing that team simulation improves team operational performance at the bedside.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Although evidence that simulation-based training actually improves patient outcome has been slow to accrue, today the ability of simulation to provide hands-on experience that translates to the operating room is no longer in doubt.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] One of the largest factors that might impact the ability to have training impact the work of practitioners at the bedside is the ability to empower frontline staff (Stewart, Manges, Ward, 2015).
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Another example of an attempt to improve patient safety through the use of simulations training is patient care to deliver just-in-time service or/and just-in-place.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] This training consists of 20 minutes of simulated training just before workers report to shift.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] One study found that just in time training improved the transition to the bedside.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] The conclusion as reported in Nishisaki (2008) work, was that the simulation training improved resident participation in real cases; but did not sacrifice the quality of service.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] It could be therefore hypothesized that by increasing the number of highly trained residents through the use of simulation training, that the simulation training does, in fact, increase patient safety.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] The first medical simulators were simple models of human patients.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Since antiquity, these representations in clay and stone were used to demonstrate clinical features of disease states and their effects on humans.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Models have been found in many cultures and continents.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] These models have been used in some cultures (e.g., Chinese culture) as a "diagnostic" instrument, allowing women to consult male physicians while maintaining social laws of modesty.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Models are used today to help students learn the anatomy of the musculoskeletal system and organ systems.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] The need for a "uniform mechanism to educate, evaluate, and certify simulation instructors for the health care profession" was recognized by McGaghie et al. in their critical review of simulation-based medical education research.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] In 2012 the SSH piloted two new certifications to provide recognition to educators in an effort to meet this need.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Active models that attempt to reproduce living anatomy or physiology are recent developments.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] The famous "Harvey" mannequin was developed at the University of Miami and is able to recreate many of the physical findings of the cardiology examination, including palpation, auscultation, and electrocardiography.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] More recently, interactive models have been developed that respond to actions taken by a student or physician.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Until recently, these simulations were two dimensional computer programs that acted more like a textbook than a patient.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Computer simulations have the advantage of allowing a student to make judgments, and also to make errors.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] The process of iterative learning through assessment, evaluation, decision making, and error correction creates a much stronger learning environment than passive instruction.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Simulators have been proposed as an ideal tool for assessment of students for clinical skills.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] For patients, "cybertherapy" can be used for sessions simulating traumatic experiences, from fear of heights to social anxiety.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Programmed patients and simulated clinical situations, including mock disaster drills, have been used extensively for education and evaluation.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] These "lifelike" simulations are expensive, and lack reproducibility.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] A fully functional "3Di" simulator would be the most specific tool available for teaching and measurement of clinical skills.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Gaming platforms have been applied to create these virtual medical environments to create an interactive method for learning and application of information in a clinical context.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Immersive disease state simulations allow a doctor or HCP to experience what a disease actually feels like.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Using sensors and transducers, symptomatic effects can be delivered to a participant, allowing them to experience the patient’s disease state.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Such a simulator meets the goals of an objective and standardized examination for clinical competence.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] This system is superior to examinations that use "standard patients" because it permits the quantitative measurement of competence, as well as reproducing the same objective findings.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] The first simulation game may have been created as early as 1947 by Thomas T.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] This was a straightforward game that simulated a missile being fired at a target.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] The curve of the missile and its speed could be adjusted using several knobs.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] In 1958, a computer game called *Tennis for Two* was created by Willy Higginbotham which simulated a tennis game between two players who could both play at the same time using hand controls and was displayed on an oscilloscope.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] This was one of the first electronic video games to use a graphical display.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Computer-generated imagery was used in the film to simulate objects as early as 1972 in *A Computer Animated Hand*, parts of which were shown on the big screen in the 1976 film *Futureworld*.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] This was followed by the "targeting computer" that young Skywalker turns off in the 1977 film *Star Wars*.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] The film *Tron* (1982) was the first film to use computer-generated imagery for more than a couple of minutes.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Advances in technology in the 1980s caused 3D simulation to become more widely used and it began to appear in movies and in computer-based games such as Atari's *Battlezone* (1980) and Acornsoft's *Elite* (1984), one of the first wire-frame 3D graphics games for home computers.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Advances in technology in the 1980s made the computer more affordable and more capable than they were in previous decades, which facilitated the rise of computer such as the Xbox gaming.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] The first video game consoles released in the 1970s and early 1980s fell prey to the industry crash in 1983, but in 1985, Nintendo released the Nintendo Entertainment System (NES) which became one of the best selling consoles in video game history.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] In the 1990s, computer games became widely popular with the release of such game as *The Sims* and *Command & Conquer* and the still increasing power of desktop computers.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Today, computer simulation games such as *World of Warcraft* are played by millions of people around the world.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] In 1993, the film *Jurassic Park* became the first popular film to use computer-generated graphics extensively, integrating the simulated dinosaurs almost seamlessly into live action scenes.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] This event transformed the film industry; in 1995, the film *Toy Story* was the first film to use only computer-generated images and by the new millennium computer generated graphics were the leading choice for special effects in films.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] The advent of virtual cinematography in the early 2000s has led to an explosion of movies that would have been impossible to shoot without it.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Classic examples are the digital look-alikes of Neo, Smith and other characters in the *Matrix* sequels and the extensive use of physically impossible camera runs in *The Lord of the Rings* trilogy.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Computer-generated imagery is "the application of the field of 3D computer graphics to special effects".
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] This technology is used for visual effects because they are high in quality, controllable, and can create effects that would not be feasible using any other technology either because of cost, resources or safety.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Computer-generated graphics can be seen in many live-action movies today, especially those of the action genre.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Further, computer-generated imagery has almost completely supplanted hand-drawn animation in children's movies which are increasingly computer-generated only.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Examples of movies that use computer-generated imagery include *Finding Nemo*, *300* and *Iron Man*.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Simulation games, as opposed to other genres of video and computer games, represent or simulate an environment accurately.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Moreover, they represent the interactions between the playable characters and the environment realistically.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] These kinds of games are usually more complex in terms of gameplay.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Simulation games have become incredibly popular among people of all ages.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Popular simulation games include *SimCity* and *Tiger Woods PGA Tour*.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] There are also flight simulator and driving simulator games.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Simulators have been used for entertainment since the Link Trainer in the 1930s.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] The first modern simulator ride to open at a theme park was Disney's Star Tours in 1987 soon followed by Universal's The Funtastic World of Hanna-Barbera in 1990 which was the first ride to be done entirely with computer graphics.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Simulator rides are the progeny of military training simulators and commercial simulators, but they are different in a fundamental way.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] While military training simulators react realistically to the input of the trainee in real time, ride simulators only feel like they move realistically and move according to prerecorded motion scripts.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] One of the first simulator rides, Star Tours, which cost $32 million, used a hydraulic motion based cabin.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] The movement was programmed by a joystick.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Today's simulator rides, such as The Amazing Adventures of Spider-Man include elements to increase the amount of immersion experienced by the riders such as: 3D imagery, physical effects (spraying water or producing scents), and movement through an environment.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p01] Another important goal of simulation in manufacturing systems is to quantify system performance.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] An automobile simulator provides an opportunity to reproduce the characteristics of real vehicles in a virtual environment.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] It replicates the external factors and conditions with which a vehicle interacts enabling a driver to feel as if they are sitting in the cab of their own vehicle.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Scenarios and events are replicated with sufficient reality to ensure that drivers become fully immersed in the experience rather than simply viewing it as an educational experience.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] The simulator provides a constructive experience for the novice driver and enables more complex exercises to be undertaken by the more mature driver.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] For novice drivers, truck simulators provide an opportunity to begin their career by applying best practice.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] For mature drivers, simulation provides the ability to enhance good driving or to detect poor practice and to suggest the necessary steps for remedial action.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] For companies, it provides an opportunity to educate staff in the driving skills that achieve reduced maintenance costs, improved productivity and, most importantly, to ensure the safety of their actions in all possible situations.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] A **biomechanics simulator** is a simulation platform for creating dynamic mechanical models built from combinations of rigid and deformable bodies, joints, constraints, and various force actuators.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] It is specialized for creating biomechanical models of human anatomical structures, with the intention to study their function and eventually assist in the design and planning of medical treatment.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] A biomechanics simulator is used to analyze walking dynamics, study sports performance, simulate surgical procedures, analyze joint loads, design medical devices, and animate human and animal movement.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] A neuromechanical simulator combines biomechanical and biologically realistic neural network simulation.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] It allows the user to test hypotheses about the neural basis of behavior in a physically accurate 3D virtual environment.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] A city simulator can be a city-building game but can also be a tool used by urban planners to understand how cities are likely to evolve in response to various policy decisions.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] AnyLogic is an example of modern, large-scale urban simulators designed for use by urban planners.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] City simulators are generally agent-based simulations with explicit representations for land use and transportation.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] UrbanSim and LEAM are examples of large-scale urban simulation models that are used by metropolitan planning agencies and military bases for land use and transportation planning.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Several Christmas-themed simulations exist, many of which are centered around Santa Claus.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] An example of these simulations are websites which claim to allow the user to track Santa Claus.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Another example of these simulations are websites that claim to allow the user to email or send messages to Santa Claus.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Websites such as emailSanta.com or Santa's former page on the now-defunct Windows Live Spaces by Microsoft use automated programs or scripts to generate personalized replies claimed to be from Santa himself based on user input.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Modern satellite communications systems (SATCOM) are often large and complex with many interacting parts and elements.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] In addition, the need for broadband connectivity on a moving vehicle has increased dramatically in the past few years for both commercial and military applications.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] To accurately predict and deliver high quality of service, SATCOM system designers have to factor in terrain as well as atmospheric and meteorological conditions in their planning.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] To deal with such complexity, system designers and operators increasingly turn towards computer models of their systems to simulate real-world operating conditions and gain insights into usability and requirements prior to final product sign-off.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Modeling improves the understanding of the system by enabling the SATCOM system designer or planner to simulate real-world performance by injecting the models with multiple hypothetical atmospheric and environmental conditions.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Simulation is often used in the training of civilian and military personnel.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] This usually occurs when it is prohibitively expensive or simply too dangerous to allow trainees to use the real equipment in the real world.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] In such situations, they will spend time learning valuable lessons in a "safe" virtual environment yet living a lifelike experience (or at least it is the goal).
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Simulation solutions are being increasingly integrated with computer-aided solutions and processes (computer-aided design or CAD, computer-aided manufacturing or CAM, computer-aided engineering or CAE, etc.).
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] The use of simulation throughout the product lifecycle, especially at the earlier concept and design stages, has the potential of providing substantial benefits.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] These benefits range from direct cost issues such as reduced prototyping and shorter time-to-market to better performing products and higher margins.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] However, for some companies, simulation has not provided the expected benefits.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] The successful use of simulation, early in the lifecycle, has been largely driven by increased integration of simulation tools with the entire set of CAD, CAM and product-lifecycle management solutions.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Simulation solutions can now function across the extended enterprise in a multi-CAD environment, and include solutions for managing simulation data and processes and ensuring that simulation results are made part of the product lifecycle history.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Simulation training has become a method for preparing people for disasters.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Simulations can replicate emergency situations and track how learners respond thanks to a lifelike experience.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Disaster preparedness simulations can involve training on how to handle terrorism attacks, natural disasters, pandemic outbreaks, or other life-threatening emergencies.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] One organization that has used simulation training for disaster preparedness is CADE (Center for Advancement of Distance Education).
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] CADE has used a video game to prepare emergency workers for multiple types of attacks.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] The Emergency Simulation Program (ESP) at the British Columbia Institute of Technology (BCIT), Vancouver, British Columbia, Canada is another example of an organization that uses simulation to train for emergency situations.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] At the University of Québec in Chicoutimi, a research team at the outdoor research and expertise laboratory (Laboratoire d'Expertise et de Recherche en Plein Air – LERPA) specializes in using wilderness backcountry accident simulations to verify emergency response coordination.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Instructionally, the benefits of emergency training through simulations are that learner performance can be tracked through the system.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] This allows the developer to make adjustments as necessary or alert the educator on topics that may require additional attention.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Other advantages are that the learner can be guided or trained on how to respond appropriately before continuing to the next emergency segment—this is an aspect that may not be available in the live environment.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Some emergency training simulators also allow for immediate feedback, while other simulations may provide a summary and instruct the learner to engage in the learning topic again.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] In a live-emergency situation, emergency responders do not have time to waste.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Simulation-training in this environment provides an opportunity for learners to gather as much information as they can and practice their knowledge in a safe environment.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] They can make mistakes without risk of endangering lives and be given the opportunity to correct their errors to prepare for the real-life emergency.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Simulation is an important feature in engineering systems or any system that involves many processes.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] For example, in electrical engineering, delay lines may be used to simulate propagation delay and phase shift caused by an actual transmission line.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Similarly, dummy loads may be used to simulate impedance without simulating propagation and is used in situations where propagation is unwanted.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] A simulator may imitate only a few of the operations and functions of the unit it simulates.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Most engineering simulations entail mathematical modeling and computer-assisted investigation.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] There are many cases, however, where mathematical modeling is not reliable.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Simulation of fluid dynamics problems often require both mathematical and physical simulations.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] In these cases the physical models require dynamic similitude.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Physical and chemical simulations have also direct realistic uses, rather than research uses; in chemical engineering, for example, process simulations are used to give the process parameters immediately used for operating chemical plants, such as oil refineries.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Simulators are also used for plant operator training.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] It is called Operator Training Simulator (OTS) and has been widely adopted by many industries from chemical to oil&gas and to the power industry.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] This created a safe and realistic virtual environment to train board operators and engineers.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Mimic is capable of providing high fidelity dynamic models of nearly all chemical plants for operator training and control system testing.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Software tools typically calculate biomechanical properties including individual muscle forces, joint forces and moments.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Most of these tools employ standard ergonomic evaluation methods such as the NIOSH lifting equation and Rapid Upper Limb Assessment (RULA).
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Some simulations also analyze physiological measures including metabolism, energy expenditure, and fatigue limits Cycle time studies, design and process validation, user comfort, reachability, and line of sight are other human-factors that may be examined in ergonomic simulation packages.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Modeling and simulation of a task can be performed by manually manipulating the virtual human in the simulated environment.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Some ergonomics simulation software permits interactive, real-time simulation and evaluation through actual human input via motion capture technologies.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] However, motion capture for ergonomics requires expensive equipment and the creation of props to represent the environment or product.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Some applications of ergonomic simulation in include analysis of solid waste collection, disaster management tasks, interactive gaming, automotive assembly line, virtual prototyping of rehabilitation aids, and aerospace product design.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Ford engineers use ergonomics simulation software to perform virtual product design reviews.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Using engineering data, the simulations assist evaluation of assembly ergonomics.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] The company uses Siemen's Jack and Jill ergonomics simulation software in improving worker safety and efficiency, without the need to build expensive prototypes.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] In finance, computer simulations are often used for scenario planning.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Risk-adjusted net present value, for example, is computed from well-defined but not always known (or fixed) inputs.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] By imitating the performance of the project under evaluation, simulation can provide a distribution of NPV over a range of discount rates and other variables.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Simulations are also often used to test a financial theory or the ability of a financial model.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Simulations are frequently used in financial training to engage participants in experiencing various historical as well as fictional situations.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] There are stock market simulations, portfolio simulations, risk management simulations or models and forex simulations.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Such simulations are typically based on stochastic asset models.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Using these simulations in a training program allows for the application of theory into a something akin to real life.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] As with other industries, the use of simulations can be technology or case-study driven.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Flight simulation is mainly used to train pilots outside of the aircraft.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] In comparison to training in flight, simulation-based training allows for practicing maneuvers or situations that may be impractical (or even dangerous) to perform in the aircraft while keeping the pilot and instructor in a relatively low-risk environment on the ground.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] For example, electrical system failures, instrument failures, hydraulic system failures, and even flight control failures can be simulated without risk to the crew or equipment.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Instructors can also provide students with a higher concentration of training tasks in a given period of time than is usually possible in the aircraft.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Flight simulation also provides an economic advantage over training in an actual aircraft.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Once fuel, maintenance, and insurance costs are taken into account, the operating costs of an FSTD are usually substantially lower than the operating costs of the simulated aircraft.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] For some large transport category airplanes, the operating costs may be several times lower for the FSTD than the actual aircraft.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Another advantage is reduced environmental impact, as simulators don't contribute directly to carbon or noise emissions.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] There also exist "engineering flight simulators" which are a key element of the aircraft design process.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Many benefits that come from a lower number of test flights like cost and safety improvements are described above, but there are some unique advantages.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Having a simulator available allows for faster design iteration cycle or using more test equipment than could be fit into a real aircraft.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Bearing resemblance to flight simulators, a **marine simulator** is meant for training of ship personnel.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Simulators like these are mostly used within maritime colleges, training institutions, and navies.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] They often consist of a replication of a ships' bridge, with the operating console(s), and a number of screens on which the virtual surroundings are projected.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Military simulations, also known informally as war games, are models in which theories of warfare can be tested and refined without the need for actual hostilities.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] They exist in many different forms, with varying degrees of realism.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] In recent times, their scope has widened to include not only military but also political and social factors (for example, the Nationlab series of strategic exercises in Latin America).
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] While many governments make use of simulation, both individually and collaboratively, little is known about the model's specifics outside professional circles.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Network and distributed systems have been extensively simulated in other to understand the impact of new protocols and algorithms before their deployment in the actual systems.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] The simulation can focus on different levels (physical layer, network layer, application layer), and evaluate different metrics (network bandwidth, resource consumption, service time, dropped packets, system availability).
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Simulation techniques have also been applied to payment and securities settlement systems.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Among the main users are central banks, which are generally responsible for the oversight of market infrastructure and are entitled to contribute to the smooth functioning of payment systems.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Central banks have been using payment system simulations to evaluate things such as the adequacy or sufficiency of liquidity available ( in the form of account balances and intraday credit limits) to participants (mainly banks) to allow efficient settlement of payments.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] The need for liquidity is also dependent on the availability and the type of netting procedures in the systems, thus some of the studies have a focus on system comparisons.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Another application is to evaluate risks related to events such as communication network breakdowns or the inability of participants to send payments (e.g. in case of possible bank failure).
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] This kind of analysis falls under the concepts of stress testing or scenario analysis.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] A common way to conduct these simulations is to replicate the settlement logics of the real payment or securities settlement systems under analysis and then use real observed payment data.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] In case of system comparison or system development, naturally, also the other settlement logics need to be implemented.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] To perform stress testing and scenario analysis, the observed data needs to be altered, e.g. some payments delayed or removed.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] To analyze the levels of liquidity, initial liquidity levels are varied.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] System comparisons (benchmarking) or evaluations of new netting algorithms or rules are performed by running simulations with a fixed set of data and varying only the system setups.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] An inference is usually done by comparing the benchmark simulation results to the results of altered simulation setups by comparing indicators such as unsettled transactions or settlement delays.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Project management simulation is simulation used for project management training and analysis.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] It is often used as a training simulation for project managers.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] In other cases, it is used for what-if analysis and for supporting decision-making in real projects.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Frequently the simulation is conducted using software tools.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] A robotics simulator is used to create embedded applications for a specific (or not) robot without being dependent on the 'real' robot.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] In some cases, these applications can be transferred to the real robot (or rebuilt) without modifications.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Robotics simulators allow reproducing situations that cannot be 'created' in the real world because of cost, time, or the 'uniqueness' of a resource.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] A simulator also allows fast robot prototyping.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Many robot simulators feature physics engines to simulate a robot's dynamics.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Such simulations can help predict the impact of how improvements in methods might impact variability, cost, labor time, and the number of transactions at various stages in the process.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] A full-featured computerized process simulator can be used to depict such models, as can simpler educational demonstrations using spreadsheet software, pennies being transferred between cups based on the roll of a die, or dipping into a tub of colored beads with a scoop.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] In sports, computer simulations are often done to predict the outcome of events and the performance of individual sportspeople.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] They attempt to recreate the event through models built from statistics.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] The increase in technology has allowed anyone with knowledge of programming the ability to run simulations of their models.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] The simulations are built from a series of mathematical algorithms, or models, and can vary with accuracy.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Accuscore, which is licensed by companies such as ESPN, is a well-known simulation program for all major sports.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] It offers a detailed analysis of games through simulated betting lines, projected point totals and overall probabilities.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] With the increased interest in fantasy sports simulation models that predict individual player performance have gained popularity.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Companies like What If Sports and StatFox specialize in not only using their simulations for predicting game results but how well individual players will do as well.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Many people use models to determine whom to start in their fantasy leagues.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Another way simulations are helping the sports field is in the use of biomechanics.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Models are derived and simulations are run from data received from sensors attached to athletes and video equipment.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Sports biomechanics aided by simulation models answer questions regarding training techniques such as the effect of fatigue on throwing performance (height of throw) and biomechanical factors of the upper limbs (reactive strength index; hand contact time).
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Computer simulations allow their users to take models which before were too complex to run, and give them answers.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Simulations have proven to be some of the best insights into both play performance and team predictability.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Simulation was used at Kennedy Space Center (KSC) to train and certify Space Shuttle engineers during simulated launch countdown operations.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] The Space Shuttle engineering community would participate in a launch countdown integrated simulation before each Shuttle flight.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] This simulation is a virtual simulation where real people interact with simulated Space Shuttle vehicle and Ground Support Equipment (GSE) hardware.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] The Shuttle Final Countdown Phase Simulation, also known as S0044, involved countdown processes that would integrate many of the Space Shuttle vehicle and GSE systems.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Some of the Shuttle systems integrated in the simulation are the main propulsion system, RS-25, solid rocket boosters, ground liquid hydrogen and liquid oxygen, external tank, flight controls, navigation, and avionics.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] The Shuttle Final Countdown Phase Simulation took place at the Kennedy Space Center Launch Control Center firing rooms.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] The firing room used during the simulation is the same control room where real launch countdown operations are executed.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] As a result, equipment used for real launch countdown operations is engaged.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] The Space Shuttle vehicle hardware and related GSE hardware is simulated by mathematical models (written in Shuttle Ground Operations Simulator (SGOS) modeling language) that behave and react like real hardware.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] During the Shuttle Final Countdown Phase Simulation, engineers command and control hardware via real application software executing in the control consoles – just as if they were commanding real vehicle hardware.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] However, these real software applications do not interface with real Shuttle hardware during simulations.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Instead, the applications interface with mathematical model representations of the vehicle and GSE hardware.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Consequently, the simulations bypass sensitive and even dangerous mechanisms while providing engineering measurements detailing how the hardware would have reacted.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Since these math models interact with the command and control application software, models and simulations are also used to debug and verify the functionality of application software.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] The only true way to test GNSS receivers (commonly known as Sat-Nav's in the commercial world) is by using an RF Constellation Simulator.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] A receiver that may, for example, be used on an aircraft, can be tested under dynamic conditions without the need to take it on a real flight.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] The test conditions can be repeated exactly, and there is full control over all the test parameters. this is not possible in the 'real-world' using the actual signals.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] For testing receivers that will use the new Galileo (satellite navigation) there is no alternative, as the real signals do not yet exist.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Predicting weather conditions by extrapolating/interpolating previous data is one of the real use of simulation.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Most of the weather forecasts use this information published by Weather bureaus.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] This kind of simulations helps in predicting and forewarning about extreme weather conditions like the path of an active hurricane/cyclone.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Numerical weather prediction for forecasting involves complicated numeric computer models to predict weather accurately by taking many parameters into account.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Strategy games—both traditional and modern—may be viewed as simulations of abstracted decision-making for the purpose of training military and political leaders (see History of Go for an example of such a tradition, or Kriegsspiel for a more recent example).
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Many other video games are simulators of some kind.
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] Such games can simulate various aspects of reality, from business, to government, to construction, to piloting vehicles (see above).
[src:simula-language/simulation-p02] However, the connection between simulation and dissembling later faded out and is now only of linguistic interest.
